619
67:02.130 --> 67:05.880
of the sequence of operations.

620
67:05.880 --> 67:13.260
Just like we had for stochastic matrices, the unitary matrices are
closed under multiplication, so you'll always get a unitary matrix

621
67:13.260 --> 67:17.070
when you compose unitary operations.

622
67:17.070 --> 67:20.070
You have to make sure
you multiply the matrices in the correct order.

623
67:20.070 --> 67:26.160
But the way it works is just like it was for
stochastic operations where the matrix for the
first operation you perform

624
67:26.160 --> 67:32.400
will always appear on the right-hand side
of the matrix product, and the last one will appear
on the left-hand side.

625
67:32.400 --> 67:41.280
So just like before, the order is reversed in the sense that you compose from right to left rather than left to right.

626
67:41.280 --> 67:48.810
Here's an interesting example that gives rise to an operation known as the square root of not operation.

627
67:48.810 --> 67:56.640
Suppose that we first
apply a Hadamard operation followed by an S operation, followed by another Hadamard operation.

628
67:56.640 --> 68:00.750
The combined action of
these three operations is described by this product.

629
68:00.750 --> 68:08.160
Here's the first Hadamard operation, here's the S operation, and here's the second Hadamard operation.

630
68:08.160 --> 68:14.310
If we perform the matrix multiplication, which isn't shown here explicitly, but you can do this for
yourself if you wish,

631
68:14.310 --> 68:20.880
the result is this matrix right here. It's a unitary matrix, and we can either check that directly

632
68:20.880 --> 68:25.650
or we can trust in the fact that the unitary matrices are
closed under multiplication.

633
68:25.650 --> 68:32.550
It has to be unitary because these three matrices are unitary as we've already seen.

634
68:32.550 --> 68:35.850
We don't have any particular
quantum state vector in mind here.

635
68:35.850 --> 68:44.580
We can imagine performing
this sequence of operations on any quantum state vector, and this matrix describes the action.

636
68:44.580 --> 68:51.360
The reason why this combined operation, meaning the one described
by this matrix right here is called a spirit of not operation,

637
68:51.360 --> 68:59.430
is that by performing it
twice, we get a not operation, or in other words, a
sigma x or an X operation.

638
68:59.430 --> 69:04.800
Performing the operation
twice is represented by squaring the matrix or
multiplying it to itself.

639
69:04.800 --> 69:09.570
And if you do this, you'll see that the result
is the Pauli x matrix.

640
69:09.570 --> 69:18.870
And that's kind of peculiar, and it gives you just a hint that you can do some interesting things with quantum information that you can't do with
classical information.

641
69:18.870 --> 69:26.790
There's no classical operation, meaning one represented
by a stochastic matrix that gives us a not operation
if we perform it twice.

642
69:26.790 --> 69:33.690
So it's a nice example that reveals that quantum operations
behave very differently from classical operations.

643
